definition.value: A trisaccharide that is alpha-L-arabinopyranose which has been glycosylated at positions 2 and 3 by alpha-L-arabinopyranosyl and beta-D-glucopyrnaosyl groups, respectively.
A beta-D-Galp-(1->6)-D-Galf in which the carbon bearing the anomeric hydroxy group has beta configuration.
An amino trisaccharide that is 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-D-glcopyranose in which the hydroxy groups at positions 4 and 6 have each been converted into the corresponding alpha-L-fucopyranosyl derivative.
An amino disaccharide that is 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-D-galactopyranose in which the hydroxy group at position 6 has been converted into the corresponding beta-L-galactopyranoside.
A disaccharide that is beta-D-glucopyranose in which the hydroxy group at position 3 has been converted into the corresponding alpha-D-xylopyranoside.
An amino disaccharide consisting of 2-amino-2-deoxy-beta-D-glucopyranose and 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose residues joined in sequence by a (1->6) glycosidic bond.
A trisaccharide that is lactose in which the hydroxy group at position 4 of the galactose ring has been converted into its alpha-L-fucopyranosyl derivative.

An amino trisacharide that is 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-beta-D-glucopyranose in which the hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 2 have been converted into the corresponding 2-O-methyl-beta-D-galactopyranosyl and alpha-L-fucopyranosyl derivatives, respectively.
A glucotriose that is D-glucopyranose in which the hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 6 have each been converted into their corresponding alpha-D-glucopyranosyl derivative.
An amino trisaccharide consisting of alpha-L-fucopyranose, beta-D-galactopyranose and 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose residues joined in sequence by (1->6) and (1->4) glycosidic bonds.
